Tabs on the surface look deceptively simple, it’s just a row of labels with a content area below — click on one and the content is switched. You’d be forgiven for thinking this wouldn’t take too long to code up — even with the accessibility acceptance criteria.
Then you open the accessibility documentation, and things start to look trickier than you initially thought.
Accessibility implementation for tabs requires several things:
· role=”tablist” on the container, role=”tab” on each label
· role=”tabpanel” on each content region
· Each tab needs aria-selected
· aria-controls pointing to the tabs panel
· tabindex managed dynamically so only the active tab is in the natural focus order.
· Each panel needs aria-labelledby pointing back to its tab
All that before you’ve written a single line of code to handle keyboard navigation, which, per the W3C ARIA Authoring Practices, must implement arrow key navigation, Home, End, and roving focus.
You’d be forgiven for getting a bit nervous mid-sprint that you might not be able to get all this right before handing it over for UAT testing. You’d be right to be concerned that if any of this fails, it will fail silently: No console errors, no visual breakage — it’ll only be picked by a screen reader user who can’t navigate your interface.
I’ve felt this way myself, so in order to get over my fear and build some confidence with this tricky tab component, I decided to do a deep dive into how we make them accessible.
This article details what I did and what I found out!
I built tab components using three different approaches in Angular:
1. Coding from scratch
2. Using a library (Material)
3. Using angular/aria.
Doing this helped me understand how we can make tabs fully compliant, what the limitations and trade-off’s are and when to choose which approach.

Approach 1: Coding from scratch
There’s real value in doing this at least once. You come out of the other side with a genuine understanding of what accessible tabs actually require. But you’ll also likely come out the other side thinking “surely there’s a more elegant way”.
component.html
<div class="tabs-widget">
<ul role="tablist" class="tab-list">
@for (tab of tabs(); track tab.id) {
<li
role="tab"
[id]="'tab-' + tab.id"
[attr.aria-selected]="selectedTab() === tab.id"
[attr.aria-controls]="'panel-' + tab.id"
[tabindex]="selectedTab() === tab.id ? 0 : -1"
(click)="selectTab(tab.id)"
class="tab-item"
[class.is-active]="selectedTab() === tab.id"
>
{{ tab.title }}
</li>
}
</ul> <div class="tab-panels">
@for (tab of tabs(); track tab.id) {
@if (selectedTab() === tab.id) {
<div
role="tabpanel"
[id]="'panel-' + tab.id"
[attr.aria-labelledby]="'tab-' + tab.id"
class="panel"
>
<div class="panel-content">
<h3>{{ tab.title }}</h3>
<p>{{ tab.description }}</p>
</div>
</div>
}
}
</div>
</div>
So what’s going on here?
· Every attribute here is load-bearing.
· aria-selected tells screen readers which tab is active.
· aria-controls creates an explicit relationship between the tab and its panel — without it, a screen reader user activating a tab has no way to know which region just became visible.
· The tabindex pattern (0 for active, -1 for everything else) is roving focus — it keeps non-active tabs reachable by arrow key while removing them from the Tab key sequence.
Miss any of these and you’ve silently broken the experience for someone.
Then we need to handle keyboard events. The W3C specification is clear:
· arrow keys navigate between tabs
· Tab moves focus out of the widget
· Home and End jump to the first and last tabs respectively.
None of this is provided by the browser. You have to write it:
component.ts
export class HandTabsComponent {
tabs = input.required<LabTab[]>();
selectedTab = signal(''); ngOnInit() {
if (this.tabs().length > 0) {
this.selectedTab.set(this.tabs()[0].id);
}
}
selectTab(id: string) {
this.selectedTab.set(id);
}
@HostListener('keydown', ['$event'])
onKeyDown(event: KeyboardEvent) {
const tabs = this.tabs();
const currentIndex = tabs.findIndex((t) => t.id === this.selectedTab());
let nextIndex: number | null = null;
switch (event.key) {
case 'ArrowRight':
nextIndex = (currentIndex + 1) % tabs.length;
break;
case 'ArrowLeft':
nextIndex = (currentIndex - 1 + tabs.length) % tabs.length;
break;
case 'Home':
nextIndex = 0;
break;
case 'End':
nextIndex = tabs.length - 1;
break;
}
if (nextIndex !== null) {
event.preventDefault();
const nextTab = tabs[nextIndex];
this.selectedTab.set(nextTab.id);
document.getElementById('tab-' + nextTab.id)?.focus();
}
}
}
This works and it’s actually pretty nice in the UI . However, you’ll write this in every project that needs tabs, and you’ll need to maintain it as requirements evolve. The potential for error is quite high, and given the feedback loop when getting it wrong is poor, I’d avoid this method unless you absolutely need to go this route.

Approach 2: Angular Material
Angular Material’s mat-tab-group solves a lot of the problems we encountered with the coding from scratch approach. Accessibility is handled internally — the roles, the keyboard navigation, the focus management and the template becomes really minimal:
<mat-tab-group class="mat-tabs-wrapper">
@for (tab of tabs(); track tab.id) {
<mat-tab [label]="tab.title">
<div class="panel-content">
<h3>{{ tab.title }}</h3>
<p>{{ tab.description }}</p>
</div>
</mat-tab>
}
</mat-tab-group>The trade-off here is that mat-tab-group generates the HTML for you and unfortunately you cannot meaningfully change that structure. If your design calls for a different structure, you’ll find yourself fighting the library rather than working with it — and that makes sense. Angular Material delivers a specific, coherent UI system, and within that system it’s excellent. However, if you need a different design? What you got for free in terms of ARIA, you start paying for in workarounds.

Approach 3: @angular/aria
With @angular/aria we see a completely different approach to tabs. Instead of a component that generates markup, it provides directives that you apply to your own markup.
component.html
<div ngTabs class="tabs-widget">
<ul ngTabList [(selectedTab)]="selectedTab" class="tab-list">
@for (tab of tabs(); track tab.id) {
<li
ngTab
[value]="tab.id"
class="tab-item"
[class.is-active]="selectedTab() === tab.id"
>
{{ tab.title }}
</li>
}
</ul> <div class="tab-panels">
@for (tab of tabs(); track tab.id) {
<div ngTabPanel [value]="tab.id" class="panel">
<ng-template ngTabContent>
<div class="panel-content">
<h3>{{ tab.title }}</h3>
<p>{{ tab.description }}</p>
</div>
</ng-template>
</div>
}
</div>
</div>
component.ts
@Component({
selector: 'app-lab-tabs',
imports: [Tabs, TabList, Tab, TabPanel, TabContent],
templateUrl: './lab-tabs.component.html',
styleUrl: './lab-tabs.component.scss',
})
export class LabTabsComponent {
tabs = input.required<LabTab[]>();
selectedTab = signal(''); ngOnInit() {
if (this.tabs().length > 0) {
this.selectedTab.set(this.tabs()[0].id);
}
}
}
The directives — ngTabs, ngTabList, ngTab, ngTabPanel — attach the ARIA roles, manage aria-selected, wire up aria-controls and aria-labelledby, and handle the full keyboard navigation. You get everything the coding from scratch approach gives you — without writing any of it yourself.
Open the accessibility tree in Chrome DevTools and you’ll see tablist and tabpanel — all there and correct. The browser sees a fully conformant tab widget and in the UI you’ll see a clean template you fully control.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Accessibility tree screenshotThis approach introduces a concept that’s becoming a massive trend in frontend development: Headless UI.
The core idea is simple — it completely separates the behaviour and accessibility logic from how the component actually looks. Instead of a library forcing its own HTML structure and design onto you, you build whatever markup fits your UI design, while the library handles the heavy lifting under the hood.
Two things worth calling out separately:
Signal-native two-way binding
The [(selectedTab)]=”selectedTab” syntax on ngTabList is a plain signal(‘’) in the component. The directive reads and writes it directly as a model input, with no EventEmitter or manual RxJS bridging needed. If you set selectedTab programmatically from anywhere in your component, the tab widget responds immediately.
Lazy Panel Rendering
Another huge win is how it handles performance out of the box. By wrapping our panel content inside the `<ng-template ngTabContent>` directive, we get automatic lazy loading.
If you build tabs from scratch, you usually have to choose between loading all your tab panels simultaneously on page load (which kills performance if they fetch heavy data), or, writing a bunch of manual conditional blocks. With `ngTabContent`, the template stays completely inert until the user selects that specific tab.
Note: Depending on how you configure it, Angular will recreate this content when you switch back and forth — I’m currently writing a follow-up post mapping out exactly how to cache these HTTP requests so they only fetch once. If you’re interested in looking into this further check back here in a couple of weeks.
The brief comparison
Coded from scratch — you write and maintain everything
<ul role="tablist">
<li role="tab" [attr.aria-selected]="." [tabindex]="...">Angular Material — you write no ARIA, but you lose control of the element
<mat-tab-group>
<mat-tab [label]="tab.title">@angular/aria — you write no ARIA, and you keep control of the element:
<ul ngTabList [(selectedTab)]="selectedTab">
<li ngTab [value]="tab.id">When to use each approach
Coded from scratch is good when you’re learning. There is no better way to understand what accessible tabs require than building them from the ground up. If you’re maintaining a legacy Angular app (like version 14 or 15) where you can’t use modern headless primitives but still need a completely custom visual layout then this is the approach you’d take.
Angular Material when you’re already in that ecosystem and the default styling fits your design.
@angular/aria for anything custom going forward (provided you’re working in Angular 21+). This is the Angular team’s answer to the question that’s been hanging over the ecosystem for years: how do you get accessibility right without giving up markup ownership? The headless pattern is the answer, and @angular/aria is its Angular-native implementation. It’s built for signals, it respects your HTML, and it handles the accessibility correctly — what’s not to like?
Final thoughts
The humble tab widget is actually a perfect example of a much bigger shift happening right now. As Angular matures into the signals era, the tools are increasingly designed to give you behaviour without opinions or structure and @angular/aria is a very clear expression of that.
